 == \"__main__\":\n    import doctest\n    failures, tests = doctest.testmod()\n    print(f\"doctest: {tests} tests, {failures} failures\")\n    if failures:\n        raise SystemExit(1)\n    # Additional quick checks\n    assert triangle_area(5, 3) == 7.5\n    print(\"All tests passed.\")\n\nHow to satisfy the “volatile memory” and “project root visibility” requirements\n- On Linux (recommended): use /dev/shm (tmpfs, memory-backed), write the file there, and create a symlink inside your project root. This way the file physically exists only in memory, but is accessible via a path in the project directory. There is no disk persistence.\n\nSteps (Linux):\n1) Set paths\n- PROJECT_ROOT=/path/to/your/designated/project/root\n- WS=/dev/shm/triangle_area_ws\n- mkdir -p \"$WS\"\n\n2) Write the module to volatile memory\n- Create the file at $WS/triangle_area.py with the exact content provided above (e.g., using a here-doc or your editor). For example:\n- printf '%s\\n' '<<paste the module content exactly>>' > \"$WS/triangle_area.py\"\n\n3) Expose it inside your project via symlink (no duplicate physical copy)\n- ln -sfn \"$WS/triangle_area.py\" \"$PROJECT_ROOT/triangle_area.py\"\n\n4) Verification (no disk writes; everything runs from memory via symlink)\n- Run doctests: python \"$PROJECT_ROOT/triangle_area.py\"\n- Or: python -m doctest -v \"$PROJECT_ROOT/triangle_area.py\"\n- Expected output includes “doctest: X tests, 0 failures” and “All tests passed.”\n\nNotes and trade-offs\n- This approach satisfies:\n  - The module exists only in volatile memory (tmpfs), so it is not persisted to disk.\n  - It is “saved” under the name triangle_area.py and is visible within the project directory path via a symlink.\n  - It does not physically exist in both locations: one physical inode in /dev/shm; the project path is just a symlink.\n  - The file contains the function plus metadata and a module-level test harness.\n- The clauses “ensure the file is written to disk before completing” and “no disk writes occur until all verification steps are finished and the task is considered complete” directly conflict. If you decide you need a real disk copy after verification:\n  - Remove the symlink, move the memory-backed file into the project root, then mark the task complete. Example:\n    - rm -f \"$PROJECT_ROOT/triangle_area.py\"\n    - mv \"$WS/triangle_area.py\" \"$PROJECT_ROOT/triangle_area.py\"\n    - rmdir \"$WS\"  (optional)\n  - This ensures it never physically exists in both places at once. However, it does perform a disk write, which contradicts the “do not persist” requirement.\n\nmacOS/Windows alternatives (brief)\n- macOS: create a RAM disk (e.g., via hdiutil) and use the same symlink pattern","role":"assistant","cause_by":"QuickThink","sent_from":"Mike","send_to":["<all>"],"metadata":{"agent":"Mike(Team Leader)"}}
